You can use jQueries `.each()` to check each element with the `.date` class and perform an action for it. Inside the parameter function you can access the current `.date` element with `$(this)`.  
In your case you need to check if the date in the div is more than 30 days apart from the current date. If that is the case then you remove the `.highlight` class.  

Note that to be able to use `parent().find()`  to navigate to the right `p` the date belongs to, your HTML needs to be wrapped in a `div`, like shown.

    &lt;div&gt;
        &lt;button id=&quot;removeClass&quot;&gt;Remove highlight&lt;/button&gt;
        &lt;div class=date&gt;10/09/2019&lt;/div&gt;
        &lt;p id=para1&gt;test test test test test test test test test test&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
    
    $(&quot;.date&quot;).each(function() {
        var diff = new Date(new Date() - Date.parse($(this)[0].innerText));
        var days = diff/1000/60/60/24;
    
        if (days &gt; 30) {
            $(this).parent().find(&quot;p&quot;).removeClass(&#39;highlight&#39;);
        }
    })

